      <hedline>
        <hl1>Liberals in Denial</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Kenneth Katzner letter disputes assertions in Anthony Lewis's May 6 Op-Ed column that overwhelming majority of liberal Americans supported West's staunch and successful resistance to Soviet Communism and look back at policy with pride (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Anthony Lewis (column, May 6) asserts, ''The overwhelming majority of liberal Americans supported the West's staunch and successful resistance to Soviet Communism, and look back at the policy with pride.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Anthony Lewis (column, May 6) asserts, ''The overwhelming majority of liberal Americans supported the West's staunch and successful resistance to Soviet Communism, and look back at the policy with pride.''</p>
        <p>Not according to their own statements, which we heard repeatedly during the Vietnam War. A favorite mantra of liberals even today is, ''Nobody won the cold war.'' Why do they say this? Because they derive no satisfaction whatever from the fact that we won it.</p>
        <p>It is time for former antiwar activists to acknowledge the obvious facts: The communization and eventual impoverishment of Vietnam was a tragedy for that country, just as it was for every country that experienced the same fate; Nazism and Communism were the twin nightmares of the 20th century. But the former activists have not been willing to say these things.</p>
        <p>KENNETH KATZNER  Washington, May 6, 2000</p>
      </block>
